04442nam a22007935i 9783110743371DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20222023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a9783110743371  a(DE-B1597)577333  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPOL0620002bisacsh1 aPetro, Nicolai N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Tragedy of Ukraine :bWhat Classical Greek Tragedy Can Teach Us About Conflict Resolution /cNicolai N. Petro. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XIII, 285 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDe Gruyter Contemporary Social Sciences ,x2747-5689 ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tA Note on Transliteration -- tChapter One What Does Athens Have to Do with Kiev? -- tChapter Two Two Nations in One State -- tChapter Three The Fatal Attraction of the Far Right -- tChapter Four The Mental Habits of Nationalism -- tChapter Five The Tragedies of Crimea and Donbass -- tChapter Six A Flawed Peace -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe conflict in Ukraine has deep domestic roots. A third of the population, primarily in the East and South, regards its own Russian cultural identity as entirely compatible with a Ukrainian civic identity. The state’s reluctance to recognize this ethnos as a legitimate part of the modern Ukrainian nation, has created a tragic cycle that entangles Ukrainian politics. The Tragedy of Ukraine argues that in order to untangle the conflict within the Ukraine, it must be addressed on an emotional, as well as institutional level. It draws on Richard Ned Lebow’s ‘tragic vision of politics’ and on classical Greek tragedy to assist in understanding the persistence of this conflict. Classical Greek tragedy once served as a mechanism in Athenian society to heal deep social trauma and create more just institutions. The Tragedy of Ukraine reflects on the ways in which ancient Greek tragedy can help us rethink civic conflict and polarization, as well as model ways of healing deep social divisions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 4aIdentität. 4aKulturelle Identität. 4aPolitische Krise. 4aUkraine. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Geopolitics.2bisacsh  aGreek tragedy.  aMaidan.  aRussia.  aUkraine.  aUkrainian politics.  aconflict resolution.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW0 cEPUBz97831107434700 cprintz978311074324140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110743371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110743371/original  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099451-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishb2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2022  aZDB-23-PLWb2022